<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100073552887296></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100073552887296><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=1441&mid=100073552887296>RE: RE: :(</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=1441&mid=100073552887296#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2507><span id=Scholar>Tomlin</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>219 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Sep 17th 10:05 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.88]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Here's my take on things:<br><br>These disciplines do not make player characters invulnerable, they simply guarantee your successfull skill check for riposte, dodge, parry, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;For example, a necromancer using Harmshield is invulnerable.  If you cast a direct damage spell on them, they will not take damage because they are invulnerable.  On the other hand, if you cast a direct damage spell on a warrior using their riposte discipline, it can still do damage to them, since they can't riposte against a spell.<br><br>Also, the damage absorption effects should not count as invulnerability.  Against invulnerable characters, any incoming damage simply doesn't happen; against characters with damage absorption effects, the incoming damage is still applied, only it gets applied to the damage absorption effect instead of the character, eventually "using up" the effect.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
